#Best Model: Regression Trees

This is a sample regression tree used in our presentation

Tree Creation

nba_stats_salary_1 <- nba_stats_salary_1 %>% select(!...1)
nba_sal_true <- nba_stats_salary_1

## 75% of the sample size

## set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(1)

dt = sort(sample(nrow(nba_sal_true), nrow(nba_sal_true)*.75))
train.nba<-nba_sal_true[dt,]
test.nba<-nba_sal_true[-dt,]

train.nba <- nba_sal_true[dt, "percent_cap"]
train.nba<- unlist(train.nba)

nba.test <- nba_sal_true[-dt, "percent_cap"]
nba.test<- unlist(nba.test)
 

#tree creation 
tree.nba <- tree(percent_cap ~.-salary -team -position,data = nba_sal_true,subset=dt,na.action = na.omit)

plot(tree.nba)
text(tree.nba,pretty = 0,cex=.77)

summary(tree.nba)

set.seed(1)

test.nba <- as.data.frame(nba_sal_true)

#bagging uses p = m = 23 

bag.nba <- randomForest(percent_cap ~ . -salary - salary_cap -name - team -season
                        -field_goal_percent -three_point_percent -free_throw_percent, 
                        data = nba_sal_true,subset = dt, 
                        mtry = 23, 
                        importance = TRUE,
                        na.action = na.omit,
                        ntree=1000)

Best Model: Random Forest

#random forest uses p/3 == 23/3 = 7 or 8 

rf.nba <- randomForest(percent_cap ~ . -salary - salary_cap -name - team -season
                        -field_goal_percent -three_point_percent -free_throw_percent, 
                        data = nba_sal_true,subset = dt, 
                        mtry = 7, 
                        importance = TRUE,
                        na.action = na.omit,
                        ntree=1000)

Boosted Model

install.packages("gbm", repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org")
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/j9/d4bvskhx3m34yf80mdwgtpr80000gn/T//Rtmp24QRE1/downloaded_packages
library(gbm)
## Loaded gbm 2.1.8.1
set.seed(1)

boost.nba <- gbm(percent_cap ~ .-salary_cap -name -salary -team -season 
                    -position -free_throw_percent -two_point_percent -three_point_percent, 
                    data = nba_sal_true[dt, ], 
                    distribution = "gaussian", 
                    n.trees =5000,interaction.depth = 6,shrinkage = .01)
                    
summary(boost.nba)

#boost.nba$fit
library(randomForest)

yhat.boost <- predict(boost.nba, newdata = nba_sal_true[-dt, ], n.trees = 1000)
boost_MSE <- mean((yhat.boost - nba.test)^2)
plot(yhat.boost, nba.test,xlab = "Predicted Percent Cap",ylab = "Actual Percent Cap",main = "Boosted Predicted Vs.Actual")
abline(0,1,col= "Red")

sqrt(boost_MSE)*100
## [1] 3.823533

I ran all the trees at multiple ntrees to find the optimal number of trees. I found very little difference between a smaller number of trees and a larger number of trees. I landed on 5000 for boosting as I found this to create the lowest RMSE error for all of the models. The boosted model had a small learning factor of .01 with a medium sized interaction depth of 6. This allowed our model to finish with a RMSE of 3.82% meaning in the early years of our data when the salary cap was around 50 million we would be within 2 million dollars of the actual salary while in the later years we were within 5 million dollars.
